<TITLE> Sri Lanka sets date for elections in war:torn east </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Colombo, April 3 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Residents in Sri Lanka's war-ravaged east will vote in provincial council elections for the first time in two decades next month, election officials in the island nation said on Thursday. The elections, part of the government's blueprint for devolution in minority Tamil areas that it hopes will go hand-in-hand with its push to win a 25-year civil war, come after the army drove Tamil Tiger rebels out of the area last year. "Eastern provincial council elections will be held on May 10," said an official at the Department of the Elections Commissioner, asking not to be named in line with policy, after nominations for the elections closed. The elections, in the eastern districts of Trincomalee, Ampara and Batticaloa, follow a smaller, dry-run local poll in the east last month, won by a government-backed party made up of former rebel fighters who defected from the Tigers in 2004. That result was seen as a blow to the Tigers, who are fighting for an independent homeland in the north and east. Officials said 1,342 candidates were contesting 37 seats in the May 10 election, which underpins the government's twin strategy to defeat the Tigers using both the ballot box and the current military offensive. The upcoming elections are aimed at entrenching a civilian administration in formerly rebel-held territory. President Mahinda Rajapaksa formally scrapped a six-year truce in January, and since then government forces have stepped up the campaign against the rebels in their northern stronghold. The same month, the government unveiled a homegrown peace plan aimed at giving more autonomy to war-torn areas. Provincial council elections are held every five years, but elections in the north and east have been repeatedly postponed because of continued fighting since 1988. Government troops drove Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels from their bastions in the east of the island around nine months a
